ion":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: \"correctly identifies\" tone suitability is model-judgment quality; mocks can verify control flow but not true detection quality. Integration is insufficient for the identification claim. MULTI-STEP: regeneration trigger is downstream orchestration, but minimum real-failure boundary is the single tone-classification decision. REJECTION-GATE: rejected Workflow because behavior does not require validating quality of multiple model outputs, only that overly formal text is detected and regeneration is triggered.","test_description":"Feed casual-tier scenarios with formally worded candidate replies to the real tone-check model/path; assert high detection rate for \"too formal\" and verify regeneration call is invoked when flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure appears when chat orchestration and persistence modules hand off multi-attempt exchange records. REAL-INFRA: can be reproduced with local/in-process DB + controllable clock; no mandatory real network/OS behavior. LLM-DEP: no dependence on model output quality, only persistence correctness. REJECTION-GATE: rejected System because behavior text is about DB record correctness/timestamps, which local integration infrastructure can catch.","test_description":"Execute conversation flow with one regeneration using real repository layer against a local test DB and fixed clock; assert stored rows include user message, first draft, regenerated draft, and expected timestamps/order.","plan_consistent":true,